Sounds exciting! I’m going to ask a few clarifying questions. Feel free to move this to dm if you prefer to answer privately

1) What made you decide to look for a technical co-founder in the first place? 

Sometimes, it's based on the belief that you need someone technical in order to build the product which in turn lets you see if people want it. If this is the case, there are often far cheaper and faster ways of getting this information

For example, there are amazing no/low code tools nowadays that can allow anyone with a computer to create beautiful landing pages and even fully functional sites/apps. Is there a barebones version of this that'll help you answer the question more easily?

Other tactics include: setting up fake ads campaigns to test clickthrough rates, doing customer/user interviews, sharing wireframes/mockups, etc.

This doesn't preclude finding a co-founder, just may help address the immediate need that you feel blocked by.

Assuming none of these tactics can unblock you, there are a bunch of different avenues to find that person. 

Usually, I like to use the occam's razor principle. I.e., who is right under your nose that you might have overlooked? Could they be suitable?

Sometimes the best and simplest answers are right in front of us.

Assuming no one, now you have to start mining your network and casting lines. 

Employ this as a multichannel strategy and be patient- sometimes the right person can take a while but it's worth the wait (& a co-founder's in this category).

Have you tried co-founder matchmaking sites, startup accelerator programs, hackathons, meetups, discords, and events for people who are interested in this area?

Important to think about your own value prop and what kind of person you're looking for. Is it for a tech startup? lifestyle business? hobby? Big differences

Last thought, but one that's important to think about is what happens if you don't find this person? Would you give up? Learn the skills to do it yourself? Hire a contractor to fill in the gaps?

Thinking about what failure looks like sometimes gives us insight into what we really need and value.

Great questions. I'm just going to scratch the surface, and will have to think if I know real experts on collector communities.

Here are a couple thoughts on 1 first. 

I would probably approach this both bottoms-up and top-down.

Top down: Take the top 10-20 collecting use cases and research for each one, has anyone built a community that has developed as a center of gravity? E.g., stamps, coins, cards, sneakers, wine. 

Note that it's possible online vs. physical worlds could have different answers.

Bottom-up: Start instead with places like reddit, hobbydb, ebay and look for collector communities that either a) are unusually consolidated, relative to their size (from top-down), or b) repeatedly link to the same 1-3 platforms. 

This may lead you to the successes, if there are any.

Once you have identified a few successes (or true positives :), it's usually much easier to then hone in on how they became successful.

Often people who've been active in the community for a while or people who built the platform but have moved on would be happy to tell you their story.

Now, onto 2, GTM strategies. 

The internet is full of stories on successful GTM strategies. 

But it's much harder to find resources on failed GTM strategies. 

And it's often from failures that we learn much more about the world (cue the Tolstoy "happy startups are all alike" ...)

IIRC, in James Collins' good to great, they did a historical comparison across many similar companies and drew conclusions about what worked and what didn't. 

This is broader than GTM but that's not a bad thing- too often we get uber focused on GTM when that's just one ingredient and maybe not even the most important.

"The Cold Start Problem" by Andrew Chen does catalog a few fatal GTM mistakes in the context of network products and at each phase. In network effects businesses, GTM is a much bigger deal IMHO.

Someone recently asked which sign in method- email, wallet, or twitter is best for a consumer crypto app

Sharing some observations after testing quite a bit over the last 9 months…

Twitter: best for nft ppl, bots, and airdrop farmers

Wallet: best for crypto natives but has a fractured UX across wallets, particularly on mobile

Farcaster: good for crypto builders, offering a middle ground between web2 UX and crypto native

Email: best for non crypto professionals

SMS is best for everyone else (granted there are security concerns)

We ended up with SMS and Farcaster as our two defaults, with a “more options” for everything else

Also we’re leaning toward adding email as a 3rd default

It is the de facto identity on the internet, reasonably secure, pretty good UX (tho magic link is annoying, esp on mobile) can be used for domain verification, and lets you reliably reengage

For now I’m bearish that crypto wallet connect can achieve the UX needed for consumer (due to several structural reasons)

Instead I think that’ll come through abstraction by using web2->web3 translation layers under the hood like privy or dynamic

OK not a whole lot new to unpack on this. 

Our TLDR is we simply leveled up our identity model from wallet address to DID to be able to accommodate many wallet addresses

Here's a thread on why...

We've been fairly confident for the last year that the correct long term architecture for identity is a cross-identity recomposable hypergraph

Here's a screenshot of our original "User ID Long Term Vision", drafted before we had even built a product

Important to us was that the true extent of a user's hypergraph can be hidden from us, yet still usable in icebreaker through recomposability.

E.g., if you have an alter ego, you should be able to traverse your complete network without having to reveal that association even to us.

This is long term, but important.

We asked around a few times to check our assumptions (https://warpcast.com/web3pm/0x211d39) and few had given much thought to it.

Identity is gnarly.

The PM responsible for unifying Google's internal identity system circa 2013 became a company hero because no one thought it could be done.

However, for us to get a shot at our long term vision of cracking identity on the internet (and trojan horse onboarding people to self-sovereign data in the process), we decided we weren't going to use tokens or gimmicks, but build a damn good networking tool that could work even in the most extreme environments

So with that goal in mind, we've been building the simplest possible version required in each phase, and only upgrading when we need to.

E.g., we used airtable for our BE up until it nearly crashed during our first big client's offsite.

For users initially, the easiest was to simply use wallet address

This approach worked up until we began adding support for multiple linked accounts about 2 weeks ago, which can now display as verified channels on any of your profiles.

In order to support additional wallets, we finally needed to uplevel our ID system to use something abstracted from a wallet address

From our work on linking, we found often users may want to rotate what wallet address they are using as a primary.

For example, if a user signs up initially with email and we create a wallet address for them, we need to support letting them map it to their real self-custody address later on.

Awkward if user = wallet

So, this week, we finally ran our upgrade, which we'd planned for some time.

I was probably most skeptical we needed it now, but our incredible engineering team   and  convinced me it was time and would significantly increase our velocity as a result.

We launched it, and soon will be adding the ability to link multiple wallets and all kinds of new things. 

Eventually we will need to uplevel our DID model again and start integrating more sophisticated stealth addressing and cross-account profiles, but first we want to crack trusted & open professional networking

END
